\section{Conclusion}
This report presented a comparative analysis of the SAITS and SSSD models for time-series imputation in a clinical context. Our results demonstrate that \textbf{SAITS} significantly outperforms SSSD and all traditional baselines, achieving the lowest error (MAE 0.0295). SSSD showed poor performance in this configuration (MAE 0.0873), performing worse than even the simple Mean Baseline. Furthermore, SSSD's inference latency ($\sim$3.7s per sample) is orders of magnitude higher than SAITS's ($\sim$24ms per sample), making SAITS the superior choice for practical clinical applications where efficiency and accuracy are paramount.
\section{Introduction}
This report details the implementation and comparative evaluation of two state-of-the-art time-series imputation models: \textbf{SAITS} (Self-Attention-based Imputation for Time Series) and \textbf{SSSD} (Structured State Space Diffusion). The evaluation is performed on the MIMIC-IV clinical dataset, focusing on 9 key physiological variables.

\section{Models and Architectures}

\subsection{SAITS}
SAITS leverages the Transformer architecture refined with a dual-block DMSA (Diagonal Masked Self-Attention) mechanism. 
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Loss Function:} A weighted combination of Masked Imputation Task (MIT) loss ($\alpha=0.8$) and Observed Reconstruction Task (ORT) loss.
    \item \textbf{Architecture:} 2 blocks of 3 encoder layers each, with 4 attention heads and a model dimension of 64.
    \item \textbf{Inference:} Non-autoregressive, single-pass attention-based imputation, optimized for speed.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{SSSD}
SSSD combines Structured State Spaces (S4) with Conditional Diffusion models.
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Backbone:} 36 S4 layers grouped into a residual architecture for long-range dependency modeling.
    \item \textbf{Process:} Iterative denoising via 1000 diffusion steps using a linear noise schedule.
    \item \textbf{Conditioning:} The model is conditioned on the observed parts of the time series via feature concatenation and additive bias in the S4 layers.
    \item \textbf{Inference:} Stochastic sampling requiring 1000 forward passes of the S4 network per imputation.
\end{itemize}

\section{Replication Methodology}
The replication was conducted on a high-性能 computing node equipped with 8 NVIDIA A100 GPUs (40GB VRAM each). The software stack included PyTorch 2.5, PyTorch Lightning, and the Hydra configuration framework.

\subsection{Data Pipeline}
The MIMIC-IV dataset was processed as follows:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Extraction:} 9 vital signs and lab results (Heart Rate, SBP, DBP, Respiratory Rate, SpO2, Creatinine, Lactate, Glucose, BUN) were extracted from the ICU stays.
    \item \textbf{Preprocessing:} Time series were discretized into 1-hour bins over a 48-hour window.
    \item \textbf{Normalization:} Features were standardized using Z-score normalization derived from the training set.
    \item \textbf{Masking:} To evaluate imputation robustly, we applied artificial masks on top of the naturally occurring missingness. Evaluation was performed using a fixed seed (\texttt{42}) on 1,000 test samples with a random masking probability of $p=0.3$.
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Execution Environment}
Parallel evaluation was implemented to overcome the latency bottlenecks of diffusion models. Specifically:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Distributed Testing:} We utilized 4 GPUs in Distributed Data Parallel (DDP) mode. 
    \item \textbf{Batch Configuration:} A global batch size of 1024 (256 per GPU) was used to maximize throughput.
\end{itemize}

